def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
PY=[
L(1,'What is Python?','Python is a beginner-friendly programming language known for its clean, readable syntax. It uses print() to display output and the = operator for variable assignment. Variable names cannot start with a number, and strings must always have matching opening and closing quotes.','print("Hello, World!")\n\nx = 5\ny = 3\nprint(x + y)  # 8\n\n# Valid variable names:\nmy_var = 10\n_count = 0\nfirstName = "Alice"\n# Invalid: 2ndPlace = True','Python uses print() for output — not echo(), console.log(), or printf(). The = sign is for assignment, == is for comparison.'),
L(1,'Variables and Assignment','Variables store data. Use a single = for assignment. Python figures out the type automatically — no need to declare it. String values must have matching quotes: missing a closing quote is a very common error.','name = "Alice"\nscore = 100\nis_active = True\n\n# This would cause an error:\n# message = "Hello World\n# (missing closing quote!)','Always close your strings with matching quotes. A missing quote will cause a SyntaxError. Use # for comments — Python ignores everything after it.'),
L(2,'Data Types','Python has several built-in types: int (whole numbers like 42), float (decimals like 3.14), str (text in quotes), bool (True or False), and list (collections in square brackets []). Use type() to check any value\'s type.','age = 25          # int\nprice = 9.99      # float\nname = "Alice"    # str\ndone = True       # bool\nitems = []        # list (empty)\n\nprint(type(3.14))   # <class \'float\'>\nprint(type(True))   # <class \'bool\'>','Remember: 3.14 is a float (not double or decimal). True/False are bool type. Square brackets [] create a list, curly braces {} create a dict.'),
L(2,'Type Conversion','Convert between types using int(), float(), str(), and bool(). This is essential when combining different types — for example, "5" + 3 would fail because you cannot add a string to a number without converting first.','num = int("25")       # str to int: 25\ntxt = str(100)        # int to str: "100"\ndec = float("3.14")   # str to float: 3.14\n\n# String concatenation vs addition:\nprint("5" + "3")      # "53" (strings)\nprint(5 + 3)          # 8 (numbers)','String concatenation joins text: "5" + "3" gives "53". To do math, convert first with int(). Converting "hello" to int() raises ValueError.'),
L(3,'String Basics','Strings are sequences of characters. Access individual characters with indexing starting at 0. Use len() to get the length. Slice strings with [start:end] syntax to extract portions.','word = "Python"\nprint(word[0])      # "P" (first char)\nprint(len(word))    # 6\nprint(word[2:5])    # "tho" (index 2,3,4)\nprint(word.upper()) # "PYTHON"','Index 0 is the first character, not 1. Slicing [6:11] extracts characters at positions 6, 7, 8, 9, 10.'),
L(3,'F-Strings and String Methods','F-strings (formatted string literals) start with f and allow embedding variables inside {} braces. Strings also have many built-in methods like .upper(), .lower(), .strip(), .replace(), and .split().','name = "Alice"\nage = 25\n\n# f-string interpolation\nprint(f"Hello, {name}!")\nprint(f"{name} is {age} years old")\n\ntext = "Hello World"\nprint(text[6:11])  # "World"','F-strings start with the letter f before the quote: f"Hello, {name}!" — the f prefix is required for variable interpolation to work.'),
L(4,'Lists','Lists hold multiple items in order using square brackets []. They are zero-indexed (first item at index 0). Use .append() to add items, len() to count items, and negative indexes like [-1] for the last item.','fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]\nfruits.append("orange")\nprint(fruits[0])    # "apple"\nprint(fruits[-1])   # "orange"\nprint(len(fruits))  # 4','Negative index -1 gives the last item, -2 gives second-to-last. Use .pop() to remove and return the last item.'),
L(4,'List References and Methods','When you assign a list to another variable with =, both variables point to the SAME list — changes through one affect the other. Use .copy() or [:] to create an independent copy.','a = [1, 2, 3]\nb = a           # same list!\nb.append(4)\nprint(a)        # [1, 2, 3, 4] (!)\n\n# To make a copy:\nc = a.copy()    # independent copy','b = a creates a reference, not a copy. Both variables point to the same list in memory. This is a very common source of bugs.'),
L(5,'If Statements','Use if, elif, and else to make decisions. Python uses colons (:) at the end of conditions and indentation to define code blocks. A missing colon after the condition is a common syntax error.','age = 18\nif age >= 18:\n    print("Adult")\nelif age >= 13:\n    print("Teenager")\nelse:\n    print("Child")','Always put a colon (:) after if, elif, and else. Python uses indentation (4 spaces) instead of curly braces for code blocks.'),
L(5,'Comparison Operators','Use == for equality comparison (not = which is assignment). Other operators: !=, <, >, <=, >=. Combine conditions with and, or, and not (Python uses words, not symbols like && or ||).','a = 5\nb = 5\nif a == b:\n    print("Equal")\n\nx = 10\nif x > 5 and x < 20:\n    print("In range")\n\nif not x == 0:\n    print("Not zero")','Python uses elif (not "else if" or "elseif"). Use == for comparison and = for assignment — mixing them up is a common mistake.'),
L(6,'For Loops','For loops iterate over sequences. Use range() to generate numbers: range(5) gives 0,1,2,3,4 (starts at 0, stops before 5). Use the for...in syntax to loop through any sequence.','for i in range(5):\n    print(i)  # 0, 1, 2, 3, 4\n\nfor i in range(1, 6):\n    print(i)  # 1, 2, 3, 4, 5\n\nfruits = ["apple", "banana"]\nfor fruit in fruits:\n    print(fruit)','range(3) generates 0, 1, 2 — it starts at 0 and stops BEFORE 3. Use range(1, 4) for 1, 2, 3.'),
L(6,'While Loops and Break','While loops keep running as long as a condition is True. Use break to exit a loop early and continue to skip to the next iteration. Be careful — forgetting to update the condition creates an infinite loop.','x = 0\nwhile x < 3:\n    x += 1\nprint(x)  # 3\n\nfor i in range(10):\n    if i == 5:\n        break\n    print(i)  # 0,1,2,3,4','The while loop ends when the condition becomes False, and x will be 3 at that point. break exits the loop immediately.'),
L(7,'Defining Functions','Use def to define functions. The return keyword sends a value back to the caller. A function without return implicitly returns None. Default parameter values are set with = in the parameter list.','def greet(name):\n    return f"Hello, {name}!"\n\nresult = greet("Alice")\nprint(result)  # Hello, Alice!\n\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a + b\n\nprint(add(3, 4))  # 7','A function that calculates but does not use return will return None. Always use return to send values back to the caller.'),
L(7,'Default Parameters','Parameters can have default values. This makes the argument optional when calling the function. Use = to set defaults. Parameters with defaults must come after parameters without defaults.','def greet(name="Guest"):\n    return f"Hello, {name}!"\n\nprint(greet())         # Hello, Guest!\nprint(greet("Alice"))  # Hello, Alice!\n\ndef order(item, qty=1):\n    print(f"{qty}x {item}")\n\norder("Coffee")        # 1x Coffee','Default parameter values use = (not : or ==). Put required parameters before optional ones.'),
L(8,'Dictionaries','Dictionaries store key-value pairs using curly braces {}. Access values by key with square brackets. Use .get(key, default) to safely access values without risking a KeyError.','person = {"name": "Alice", "age": 25}\nprint(person["name"])     # Alice\nperson["email"] = "a@b.com"  # add new\nprint(len(person))        # 3\n\n# Safe access with default:\nprint(person.get("phone", "N/A"))','Use .get("key", default) instead of ["key"] to avoid KeyError when a key might not exist.'),
L(8,'Dictionary Methods','Useful methods: .keys() returns all keys, .values() returns all values, .items() returns key-value pairs as tuples. Loop through dictionaries with for key, value in dict.items().','scores = {"math": 90, "english": 85}\n\nfor subject, score in scores.items():\n    print(f"{subject}: {score}")\n\nprint(list(scores.keys()))  # ["math", "english"]\n\nd = {"x": 10}\nd["y"] = 20\nprint(len(d))  # 2','Adding a new key to a dictionary increases its length. len(d) returns the number of key-value pairs.'),
L(9,'Opening and Reading Files','Use open() with a with statement to handle files safely. The with block automatically closes the file when done. Mode "r" reads, "w" writes (overwrites), and "a" appends to the end.','with open("data.txt", "r") as f:\n    content = f.read()\n    print(content)\n\n# Read all lines into a list:\nwith open("file.txt", "r") as f:\n    lines = f.readlines()','Use .read() for entire file content, .readlines() for a list of lines. The "a" mode appends data without overwriting.'),
L(9,'Writing Files and Best Practices','Always use the with statement to ensure files are properly closed. Without it, you must manually call f.close(). Opening a file without closing it can cause data loss and resource leaks.','# Good: with statement\nwith open("output.txt", "w") as f:\n    f.write("Hello!")\n\n# Bad: manual open without close\nf = open("data.txt", "r")\ncontent = f.read()\n# f.close() is missing!','Always close files properly. The with statement is best practice — it handles closing automatically even if an error occurs.'),
L(10,'Try and Except','Handle errors gracefully with try/except. The try block contains code that might fail, and except catches specific exception types. The finally block always runs, regardless of whether an error occurred.','try:\n    result = 10 / 0\nexcept ZeroDivisionError:\n    print("Cannot divide by zero")\nfinally:\n    print("This always runs")\n\ntry:\n    x = int("abc")\nexcept:\n    print("Error")  # Catches any exception','The else block runs only when no exception occurs. finally always runs. Use specific exception types when possible.'),
L(10,'Raising Exceptions','Use raise to throw your own exceptions when invalid data is detected. Common exception types: ValueError, TypeError, KeyError, IndexError. Accessing index 10 in a 5-element list raises IndexError.','age = -5\nif age < 0:\n    raise ValueError("Age cannot be negative")\n\nnums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\ntry:\n    print(nums[10])  # IndexError!\nexcept IndexError:\n    print("Index out of range")','IndexError occurs when accessing an index beyond the list size. KeyError occurs when accessing a missing dictionary key.'),
L(11,'List Comprehensions','A compact way to create lists by combining a loop and an expression in one line. Add an if clause to filter items. Each item in range(4) — which gives 0,1,2,3 — gets multiplied by 2.','nums = [x * 2 for x in range(4)]\nprint(nums)  # [0, 2, 4, 6]\n\nevens = [x for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]\nprint(evens)  # [0, 2, 4, 6, 8]\n\nwords = ["hello", "world"]\nupper = [w.upper() for w in words]','The if clause filters items: [x for x in nums if condition] keeps only items where the condition is True.'),
L(11,'Dict and Set Comprehensions','Comprehensions also work for dictionaries and sets. Use {key: value for ...} for dicts and {value for ...} for sets. Nested comprehensions can flatten matrices.','# Dict comprehension\nsquares = {x: x**2 for x in range(5)}\n# {0:0, 1:1, 2:4, 3:9, 4:16}\n\n# Set comprehension\nunique = {x % 3 for x in range(10)}\n# {0, 1, 2}\n\n# Flatten a matrix\nmatrix = [[1,2],[3,4]]\nflat = [n for row in matrix for n in row]','Keep comprehensions readable. If one gets too complex (multiple loops + conditions), use a regular for loop instead.'),
L(12,'Custom Exceptions','Create your own exception classes by extending the Exception base class. Custom exceptions make error handling more specific and meaningful in your application.','class InsufficientFunds(Exception):\n    pass\n\ndef withdraw(balance, amount):\n    if amount > balance:\n        raise InsufficientFunds(\n            f"Need {amount}, have {balance}")\n    return balance - amount','Custom exceptions should inherit from Exception. Use pass as the body if no extra functionality is needed.'),
L(12,'Exception Chaining and Else','Use raise ... from ... to chain exceptions and preserve the original error context. The else block in try/except runs only when no exception occurred — useful for code that should only run on success.','try:\n    value = int("abc")\nexcept ValueError as e:\n    raise RuntimeError("Bad input") from e\n\n# else block\ntry:\n    x = int("42")\nexcept ValueError:\n    print("Invalid")\nelse:\n    print(f"Success: {x}")  # runs only if no error','The else block runs only when try succeeds. This separates the "risky" code from the "success" code cleanly.'),
L(13,'Classes and Objects','A class is a blueprint for creating objects. The __init__ method runs automatically when creating a new object. self refers to the current instance and is required as the first parameter of every method.','class Dog:\n    def __init__(self, name, breed):\n        self.name = name\n        self.breed = breed\n    \n    def bark(self):\n        return f"{self.name} says Woof!"\n\ndog = Dog("Rex", "Labrador")\nprint(dog.bark())','__init__ is the constructor — it sets up the object when created. self.name stores data on the object instance.'),
L(13,'Inheritance','A child class inherits all attributes and methods from its parent class. It can add new methods or override existing ones. Use super().__init__() to call the parent class constructor.','class Animal:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n    def speak(self):\n        return "..."\n\nclass Cat(Animal):\n    def speak(self):\n        return f"{self.name} says Meow"\n\ncat = Cat("Whiskers")\nprint(cat.speak())','Use super().__init__() inside the child __init__ to call the parent constructor and set up inherited attributes.'),
L(14,'Importing Modules','Modules are Python files with reusable code. Use import to load built-in modules like math, random, and os. Use from module import name to import specific items.','import math\nprint(math.sqrt(16))  # 4.0\n\nfrom random import randint\nprint(randint(1, 10))\n\nimport os\nprint(os.getcwd())','Use from module import * carefully — it can cause name conflicts. Prefer explicit imports.'),
L(14,'Creating Your Own Modules','Any Python file can be a module. Save functions in a .py file and import them in other files. Use if __name__ == "__main__": for code that should only run when executed directly.','# helpers.py\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a + b\n\n# main.py\nfrom helpers import add\nprint(add(3, 4))  # 7','if __name__ == "__main__": prevents code from running when the file is imported as a module by another file.'),
L(15,'Decorators','Decorators wrap a function to add extra behavior without modifying the original function. Use the @decorator syntax above a function definition. Common built-in decorators include @staticmethod, @classmethod, and @property.','def timer(func):\n    import time\n    def wrapper(*args):\n        start = time.time()\n        result = func(*args)\n        elapsed = time.time() - start\n        print(f"Took {elapsed:.2f}s")\n        return result\n    return wrapper\n\n@timer\ndef slow():\n    import time; time.sleep(1)\nslow()','The @decorator syntax is shorthand for: func = decorator(func). Decorators are functions that take a function and return a modified version.'),
L(15,'Generators','Generators produce values one at a time using yield instead of return. They save memory when working with large datasets because they do not store all values at once.','def countdown(n):\n    while n > 0:\n        yield n\n        n -= 1\n\nfor num in countdown(5):\n    print(num)  # 5, 4, 3, 2, 1\n\n# Generator expression\nsquares = (x**2 for x in range(1000))','Generator expressions use parentheses instead of brackets: (x**2 for x in range(n)) creates values on demand.'),
]
